Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Our dataset contains 1599 observations and 11 quantitative variables. This is a tidy data set that describes each observation (red variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine) with 11 qualitative physicochemical input variables and 1 output variable: quality. I’ll try to analyze which variables define red wine quality for this particular sample. There are some interesting facts about variables that could relate to quality:

  • Volatile acidity: at too high of levels can lead to unpleasant, vinegar taste.
  • Citric acid: can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines.
  • Free sulfur dioxide: prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine (SO2).
  • Total sulfur dioxide: over 50 ppm becomes evident in the nose and taste.
  • Density: dependent variable of alcohol and sugar.
  • pH: how acid or basic is the wine, most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale.
  • Sulphates: additive which can contribute to S02 levels.
  • Alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Volatile acidity, citric acid, sulphates and alcohol are interesting since they are multimodal. Is there a relation between each mode and quality?

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Since Fixed acidity and pH are related to citric and volatile acidity those are other variables I would like to analyze. As for alcohol, it looks like there is a relation to density and sugar residual that we need to verify.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Not yet but Density, pH and Fixed acidity can eventually be removed if we managed to conclude they can be highly correlated to other varibles linearly related to quality.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Sugar residuals, chlorides, sulphates and total sulfur dioxide look normal once outliers are applied. Residual Sugar and Sulphates are even alike.

Some are normal distributions like Ph and Density but in most cases the distributions are right skewed. I applied a scale_y_sqrt to the plots to amplify the modals and see other patterns.

Observations:

  • Fixed Acidity mean increases as quality increases with a peak at 8.8 g/dm^3. Almost logistic but with more variance at quality level 8.
  • Volatile acidity decreases as quality increases and has less variance as quality increases as well.
  • Citric acid follow a positive linear behaviour as quality increases.
  • Residual Sugar doesn’t have a linear behaviour with quality.
  • Chlorides (once ouliers are excluded) seems to follow a linear model against quality by looking at conditional summary.
  • The same goes for pH and density. There is a relation with quality but not completely linear.
  • Alcohol has a strong correlation to quality except for level 5 but as the violin plot shows it shows outliers and particular behaviour compared to other levels.
  • Sulphates seems to have a linear pattern to quality.

Multivariate Analysis

By selecting the variables that are more related to quality grouped by: 1. Alcoholic (excluding density and suger residuals since are related to alcohol) 2. Acidity (volatile, since others like pH, Citric and Fixed are related as well) 3. Sulphates 3. Chloridic 4. SO2 (i included SO2 since it improved the model a little bit)

This is the model:

m1 <- lm(quality ~ alcohol, data = pf)
m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + volatile.acidity)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + I(log(sulphates)))
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + chlorides)
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + total.sulfur.dioxide)
mtable(m1, m2, m2, m3, m4, m5)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I focused on those variables with high correlation to quality and more linear behaviour:

  • Alcohol
  • Volatile acidity
  • Sulphates (logistic)
  • Chlorides

Other variables were not used to prevent redundancy, for example, citric acid, fixed acidity, pH and density are related to Volatile Acidity anyway.

Density is also related to alcohol. Sugar Residual and SO2 were not highly related to quality. I included Total SO2 to improve some more the model but it’s marginal.

Even with the model its quite difficult to get a model with a strongher Rsquared since for some quality levels there are not enough observations. That’s why I opted to collapese and merge some levels.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Yes, density requires more analysis and SO2 variables as well since they show complex relations to quality.

Reflection

The model was simple in the sense that all variables were continuos. Plotting distributions and relationships was easy with ggplot and specially ggpairs to see multiple plots at once is just great. Using violin-plots to identify the impact of outlier and strange distributions is great too. But at the end one of the main tools I used to double check my finding was the conditional summaries table.

Once I analyzed relationship between input variables I decided to go for 4 variables since they were related to quality and they also had strong relations to other “secondary” variables like citric acid, pH, density, sugar residual and fixed acidity.

  • Alcohol
  • Volatile acidity
  • Sulphate
  • Chloride

I thouht Citric Acid would play a mayor role in my model but at the end it didn’t help that much.

Challenges:

Quality levels with just a few observations. I spent the last weeks trying to figure it out how to deal with just a few observations at quality level 3 and 8. Without using inference statistics I opted to grouped those categories to see more patterns and then decide an approach.

Most variables don’t have a well defined linear relationship with quality variable so more complex analysis need to be applied to improve the model. For example SO2 variables have concave shapes.

Removing or hidding outliers. In most cases I just used coord_cartesian to visually exlude them without affecting the results since I didn’t had much more information to decide it they were contamination or valid data.

Future analysis:

Quality level 5 for chlorides, sugar residuals, sulphates and alcohol clearly shows in violin plots the effect of outliers in that particular group. I opted to leave the outliers but it would be interesting to see that particular quality level in detail and fine tune some more the model.

Density is an interesting variable. It links acidity variables and alcohol/sulfur variables and has a great pattern to model classification since quality levels seems to follow linear models as well.
